uiLabel: draft sequence repository contextual data standard
uiDefinition: This draft specification provides a collection of fields related to the contextual data of a specimen, its genomic sequencing, and its pathogenic epidemiology.
Contact information for an organization related to specimen collection, processing or storage.
The role played by an organization in a process e.g. sample collection, microbial isolation, sequencing, bioinformatics.
The name of the organization.
A first name is a name that denotes a specific individual between members of a group of individuals, whose members usually share the same surname.
A last name (surname) is a name added to a given name and is part of a personal name and is often the family name.
The name of the job position held by the contact.
help: Where personnel turnover may affect the ability for follow up, the contact information can be supplied for a job position rather than a specific individual.

uiDefinition: An email address is an identifier to send mail to particular electronic mailbox.
A telephone number is an identifier used to connect to a physical device capable of transferring voice or data over a network.
A sequence of decimal digits (0-9) that is used for identifying a destination telephone line or other device in a telephone network.
The name of the country in which the organization is located.
The name of the Province, State, Territory or Region in which the organization is located.

uiLabel: Heard Island and McDonald Islands Territory
Territory of Ashmore and Cartier Islands

uiDefinition: The name of the city, town or village in which the organization is located.

uiLabel: populated place, Democratic Republic of Congo
populated place, Republic of South Africa
populated place, contiguous United States of America

uiDefinition: The street address describes the physical (geographic) location of the laboratory facility.
help: The Street Address should include the building number and street name.

uiDefinition: The type of material from which the isolate was obtained. Samples are usually categorized as food, body products or tissues, or environmental material.
A geographic location where a given specimen was extracted or collected from. Location can be identified at country, city, postal address, or longitude and latitude level of granularity.
An anthropogenic geographic feature is a geographic feature resulting from the influence of human beings on nature.
A biome is an environmental system to which resident ecological communities have evolved adaptations.
The geographical origin of the sample by city, region, country or latitude and logitude.

help: Use ISO 6709 standard. Values should be stored in signed decimal degrees format based on the WGS84 geodetic reference system. Multiple value pairs may be entered if the site is not a point. Latitude and longitude should not be abstracted to the centre of a city, province/state or country as this may falsely implicate an existing location.

uiDefinition: A decimal longitude measurement in degrees in conformance with the ISO 6709 standard.
A decimal latitude measurement in degrees in conformance with the ISO 6709 standard.
The country in which the sample was collected.
The name of the Province, State, Territory or Region where the sample was extracted from.
The city in which the sample was collected.
The date the sample was collected.
help: The sample collection date should be recorded as YYYY-MM-DD according to ISO 8601.

uiDefinition: The process used to collect the sample e.g. phlebotomy, lavage, necropsy.
help: Collection Methods are not always known, however when specified, they should be selected from an ontology controlled vocabulary.

uiDefinition: The instrument or container used collect the sample e.g. swab, tube.
help: Collection Devices are not always known, however when specified, they should be selected from an ontology controlled vocabulary.

uiDefinition: A portion of an absorbent material attached to one end of a small stick for the purpose of applying or collecting material.
A hollow cylinder, especially one for holding or conveying liquids.
A substance obtained from the natural or built environment e.g. soil, water, manure.
help: Food is considered to be a separate field from Environmental Material.

uiDefinition: An environmental location may describe a site in the natural or built environment e.g. abattoir, retail outlet, feedlot, food processing machinery.
help: Food-related environmental locations may include, but are not exclusive to, food production, processing, distribution and retail environments that were sampled. Where Environmental Locations apply, descriptors should be selected from an ontology controlled vocabulary. Format: Ontology\nSource: GenEpiO slim, FoodOn slim, or EnvO

uiDefinition: An animal (including humans) or plant or part thereof, that nourishes and supports a pathogen either in a lab or natural environment.
Health or disease status of specific host at time of collection e.g. healthy, diseased.

uiLabel: Death During, or within 90 Days of, Index Hospital Admission

uiDefinition: An abnormal condition, or disorder of a structure or function, of a host due to the action of a pathogen.
The substance produced by the body from which the isolate was obtained from e.g. feces, cerebral spinal fluid, mucus.
help: Body Products may refer to animal or plant samples as well as clinical samples. Body Products are considered to be anatomical substances that can move through a body. Tissue types should be specified in the Anatomical Site field.

uiDefinition: An anatomical location such as a specific organ or tissue e.g. caecum, duodenum.
help: Anatomical sites can pertain to both clinical, animal and plant samples. Materials that move through a body (e.g. feces, urine, blood) should be specified in the Body Products field.

uiLabel: structure with developmental contribution from neural crest

uiDefinition: The species of the isolate being sequenced.

uiDefinition: The characterization of an organism based on the antigenic properties of the molecules on its surface.
A strain is a population of organisms that is genetically different (considered a uniform population) from others of the same species, and possessing a set of defined characteristics.

An isolate is a population of microbial cells in pure culture derived from a single colony on an isolation plate. Different isolates can be the same strain, but different strains cannot be the same isolate.
a processed material that provides the needed nourishment for microorganisms or cells grown in vitro.
The selective material used to isolate the organism being sequenced from others in the sample.
The number of serial iterations that an isolate is grown in one environment.
The procedure used to serially propagate an isolate in an environment.
help: The Passage Protocol should include, when applicable, inoculum size, media type, temperature and duration of incubation.

uiDefinition: This specification offers food source, product type, packaging and processing attributes relevant to describing a food specimen.
A food specimen type is a categorization of a food specimen, by the organism it is or came from, or by a class of food products.
Individual plant or animal from which the food product or its major ingredient is derived; also a chemical food source [FDA CFSAN 1995].

uiDefinition: A dataset of the minimal inhibitory concentrations (value, unit, sign (<,>, =)) and resistance phenotypes (resistant, sensitive or undetermined) of the sequenced isolate against different antibiotics tested.
This is the minimal set of parameters for drug test results for a particular antimicrobial agent.
The standard chemical name for a drug.
help: Standard chemical or generic drug names, rather than common or brand names, should be selected from an ontology controlled vocabulary.

uiDefinition: The numerical value of the MIC e.g. 4.
A MIC test measurement resulting from a laboratory diffusion method.
A MIC test measurement resulting from a laboratory diffusion method.
The standard unit of the MIC e.g. g/mL.
The sign of the MIC indicates whether the concentration can be precisely determined (denoted by = sign), or is in range below (<) or above (>) the value given.

The resistance phenotype of an isolate represents the interpretation of an MIC value with regard to some breakpoint threshold e.g. resistant (R), sensitive (S), intermediate (I), wild type (WT), or non-wild type (NWT).
help: The Resistance Phenotype depends on the breakpoint thresholds applied, which in turn depend on the reference standard used for interpretation. Breakpoints can also be host, organism, drug, and infection site-specific. In cases where a standard requires Host, Organism, Drug Name, and Tissue Specificity (AST Breakpoint) information for the appropriate selection of breakpoints, these should be specified.

uiDefinition: The name of the tissue type used to select breakpoints from a particular standard, for the interpretation of MIC results.
help: Tissue Specificity (AST Breakpoint) only needs to be specified when the standard used to interpret the MIC requires this information e.g. selecting CLSI veterinary breakpoints.

uiDefinition: The type of assay used to determine the MIC e.g. broth dilution.
The lowest value of the drug tested e.g. 0.
help: The Minimum Drug Concentration Tested should be given as a numerical value. The units will be assumed to be the same as the MIC.

uiDefinition: The highest value of the drug tested e.g. 128.
help: The Maximum Drug Concentration Tested should be given as a numerical value. The units will be assumed to be the same as the MIC.

uiDefinition: The commercial kit or product used to determine the MIC e.g. E-Test. If a commercial product was not used, include the type of media used.
The clinical and laboratory guidelines or standards that prescribe the threshold values for determining resistance phenotypes. e.g. CLSI.
The instrumentation used to determine MIC values e.g. Vitek.
The date the isolate was sequenced.
help: The sequencing date should be recorded as YYYY-MM-DD according to ISO 8601.

uiDefinition: The procedure used to remove adapters from raw sequence reads, trim low quality bases and where applicable, merge paired-end reads.
help: Include name and version of trimming tool and if applicable, paired-end merger program. It is recommended that parameters are also recorded.

uiDefinition: the removal of adapter sequences from demultiplexed data reads
The name and version of the software product used for removal of adapter sequences from demultiplexed data reads
The name and version of the software used to merge paired-end reads before assembly.
The procedure used to remove low quality reads and unalignable sequences from raw sequence data.
help: Include the name and version of filtering tool(s) and processes applied.

uiDefinition: The nutrient material used to grow or maintain the organism being sequenced.
The procedure used to obtain genomic DNA from a sample through chemical, physical or mechanical means.
help: Include the name of the commercial kit and version number, or laboratory protocol, used to extract the genomic DNA of the isolated organism.

uiDefinition: A sequencing technical replicate represents the resequencing of the same colony in order to assess experimental variation.\nA sequencing biological replicate represents a sequencing experiment based on a different colony from the same isolate obtained from the same sample material, in order to assess biological variation.
help: Replicates within a set of sequencing runs should be described as either technical or biological.

uiDefinition: The procedure used to create a library from fragments of DNA using oligonucleotides with the role of adaptors.
help: Include the name of the commercial kit and version number, or laboratory protocol, used to prepare libraries for sequencing.

uiDefinition: The version identifier of a packaged kit tailored for specific sequencing workflows.
The system of reactions, reactants and conditions used to identify the order of nucleotides in a piece of DNA.
The type of machine used to automate the process of sequencing.
The method or algorithm used to assemble individual sequence reads into larger contiguous sequences (contigs).
help: Describe the bioinformatics pipeline used, including the name and version of assembler software, and accession number of the reference genome used in the case of reference-based assembly. It is recommended that parameters are also recorded.

uiDefinition: The method or algorithm used to identify and report sequence features (e.g. protein coding regions) in sequence data.
help: Include the name and version of annotation tool. It is recommended that parameters are also recorded.

uiDefinition: Measurements or calculated quantities used to assess the extent and success of the sequence assembly process. Metric thresholds are species-specific.
The breadth of coverage is the percentage of the genome that was sequenced to a prescribed depth of coverage.
help: Breadth of coverage should be reported as a percentage value (e.g. 95%) to a fold of coverage (e.g. 10X).

uiDefinition: The total number of base pairs contained in assembled contigs.
help: The size of the assembled genome should be reported as a numerical value in Mb e.g. 5.2 Mb.

uiDefinition: The mean contig length is the count of base pairs in the average size contig of the sequence assembly.
The total number of contiguous sequences containing all of the assembled sequence data.
help: Number of contigs should be reported as a numerical value e.g. 5.

uiDefinition: Sequencing depth is the average number of reads representing a given nucleotide in the reconstructed sequence.
help: Sequencing depth should be reported as a numerical value as X times fold e.g. 30x

uiDefinition: Contig or scaffold N50 is a weighted median statistic such that 50% of\nthe entire assembly is contained in contigs or scaffolds equal to or larger than this value.
help: N50 should be reported as a numerical value in Mb e.g. 0.75 Mb

uiDefinition: The virulence factors determined to be present in the sequenced isolate by phenotypic or target amplification methods e.g. Shiga toxins, hemolysins.
The name of the virulence factor molecule produced by a pathogen that specifically causes disease, or that influences the host's function to allow the pathogen to thrive.
The laboratory protocol used to determine virulence phenotypes and markers.
help: The protocol for determining virulence should include, when applicable, inoculum preparation, platforms and instrumentation, conditions, cell lines and animal models.

uiDefinition: The detection limit denotes the smallest measure that can be detected with reasonable certainty for a given analytical procedure.
help: Detection limits should include the numerical cut-off (threshold) value and units for determining positive results e.g. qPCR value, CFUs.

uiDefinition: Name of strain from which sample was obtained OR name of isolate from which sample was obtained.
help: This information can be derived exactly from the ISO Strain or Isolate field. Only one value should be provided, at the discretion of the submitter.

uiDefinition: Taxon identifier OR scientific name of the organism that provided the sequenced genetic material.

uiDefinition: Serological variety of a species characterized by its antigenic properties.

Identifies sequences derived by direct molecular isolation from a bulk environmental DNA sample (by PCR with or without subsequent cloning of the product, DGGE, or other anonymous methods) with no reliable identification of the source of the organism.
help: used only with the source feature key; source feature keys containing the /environmental_sample qualifier should also contain the /isolation_source qualifier. entries including /environmental_sample must not include the /strain qualifier

uiDefinition: Date that the specimen was collected, in format YYYY-MM-DD.
help: This information can be derived from the ISO Collection Date field. If the stakeholder must include a truncated version due to data sharing constraints, only include the year (YYYY format).

uiDefinition: Name of persons or institute who collected the specimen.
A word or group of words indicating the identity of a person usually consisting of a first (personal) name and a last (family) name with an optional middle name.
A textual identifier for an organization. [def-source: NCI]

Geographical coordinates of the location where the specimen was collected OR locality of isolation of the sampled organism indicated in terms of political names for nations, oceans or seas, followed by regions and localities.
help:
Only lat_lon or country information should be provided, at the discretion of the submitter.*
Lat_lon information can be derived by concatenating a subset of the ISO Geographic Location of Sample Collection fields prescribed by Annex
B. Specifically, Latitude and Longitude information should be concatenated and separated by a space.
Country information can be derived exactly from the ISO Country field in Annex B.

Use ISO 6709 standard. Values should be stored in signed decimal degrees format based on the WGS84 geodetic reference system. Multiple value pairs may be entered if the site is not a point. Latitude and longitude should not be abstracted to the centre of a city, province/state or country as this may falsely implicate an existing location.

uiDefinition: A decimal longitude measurement in degrees in conformance with the ISO 6709 standard.
A decimal latitude measurement in degrees in conformance with the ISO 6709 standard.
The country in which the sample was collected.
The name of the Province, State, Territory or Region where the sample was extracted from.
The city in which the sample was collected.
Describes the physical, environmental and/or local geographical source of the biological sample from which the sample was derived.
help: This information can be derived by concatenating the information for Sample Type and related fields, separated by a colon.

uiDefinition: An anthropogenic geographic feature is a geographic feature resulting from the influence of human beings on nature.
A biome is an environmental system to which resident ecological communities have evolved adaptations.
Natural (as opposed to laboratory) host to the organism from which sample was obtained (or free-living if not host-associated).
